\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces Distributions of non-zero surface-hail diameters produced across all simulated time steps by microphysics scheme, comparing diameters produced by the microphysics scheme at the lowest model level (``MP scheme'') and those produced by HAILCAST. P3-3M does not calculate a near-surface hail diameter. Numbers under each bar show the number of simulations that produced damaging ($>$ 20 mm) hail.}}{4}{}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Simulation locations. Each location corresponds to a satellite detection for which four simulations were produced. Markers representing the microphysics (MP) scheme and whether the simulation produced surface hail surround each detection location. The x and y axes show longitude and latitude, respectively, and the globe shows the study location (shaded red) in context.}}{5}{}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces Distributions of minimum and maximum environmental parameters over all simulated time steps, grouped by microphysics scheme and by whether the simulated hail detection produced surface hail. Each detection is considered as a whole, so ``surface hail'' here includes time steps for which there was no surface hail if there was surface hail in the same event. Bars show medians, boxes show interquartile ranges (IQRs), whiskers show range of points within 1.5$\times $IQR, and points show points outside that range. Radar reflectivity is simulated 10 cm reflectivity. Freezing level height is the height of wet-bulb 0 $^{\circ }$C temperature. CAPE is convective available potential energy and CIN is convective inhibition, both calculated using a well-mixed parcel over the lowest 100 hPa. We note that P3-3M does not have a graupel hydrometeor category.}}{6}{}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces Skew-T log-P plots showing mean profiles for all simulations that produced surface hail (H, pink) and those that did not produce surface hail (NH, green), by microphysics scheme. Black lines show the lifted temperature profiles for the mean 1000 hPa parcel across all simulations for each microphysics scheme.}}{7}{}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5}{\ignorespaces Mean vertical profiles (solid lines) and the standard deviation (shaded regions) across all time steps, for cloud, rain, ice, graupel, and hail hydrometeor mixing ratios. Each row shows a different microphysics scheme and the profiles are coloured by whether the included time steps were in a hail or no-hail event. The P3-3M microphysics scheme has no graupel-only or hail-only ice category, while the Thompson microphysics scheme does not have a hail category.}}{13}{}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6}{\ignorespaces As for Figure \ref {fig:hydrometeors}, but for relative humidity, U, V, and W winds, and radar reflectivity (Z).}}{14}{}%
